{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Fine-Tuning Machine Learning Models via Hyperparameter Search\n","\n","In machine learning, we typically have two types of parameters: those learned from the training data (e.g., weights in logistic regression) and hyperparameters, which are parameters of the learning algorithm itself that must be optimized separately (e.g., the regularization parameter $C$, or the depth of a decision tree).\n","\n","To find the optimal combination of hyperparameter values, we rely on search algorithms.\n","\n","---"],"metadata":{"id":"tP3Fl_sv0QgP"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import pandas as pd\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder\n","from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n","\n","\n","# 1. Read in the dataset directly from the UCI website using pandas\n","df = pd.read_csv('https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/breast-cancer-wisconsin/wdbc.data', header=None)\n","\n","# 2. Assign features to X and labels to y, then encode labels\n","X = df.loc[:, 2:].values\n","y = df.loc[:, 1].values\n","\n","le = LabelEncoder()\n","y = le.fit_transform(y)\n","\n","print(le.transform(['M', 'B']))\n","\n","# 3. Divide the dataset into training and test splits\n","X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n","    X, y, test_size=0.20, stratify=y, random_state=1\n",")"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"P_Wm3KC707JC","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779120227099,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":1824,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"2ced2b34-ab2e-4396-d281-624a5425abe4"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["[1 0]\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["\n","## 1. Grid Search (`GridSearchCV`)\n","\n","Grid search is a brute-force exhaustive search paradigm where we specify a list of values for different hyperparameters. The computer then evaluates the model performance for every combination of these values to find the optimal set.\n","\n","### Implementation\n","\n","In this example, we use a Support Vector Machine (SVM) pipeline and tune its parameters: the linear kernel's regularization parameter $C$, and the RBF kernel's $C$ and $\\gamma$ parameters."],"metadata":{"id":"X35JieK11Ash"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV\n","from sklearn.svm import SVC\n","from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n","\n","# Create a pipeline with a standard scaler and SVM classifier\n","pipe_svc = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), SVC(random_state=1))\n","\n","# Define the parameter range to test\n","param_range = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0, 1000.0]\n","\n","# Define the grid of parameters\n","param_grid = [\n","    {'svc__C': param_range, 'svc__kernel': ['linear']},\n","    {'svc__C': param_range, 'svc__gamma': param_range, 'svc__kernel': ['rbf']}\n","]\n","\n","# Initialize GridSearchCV with 10-fold cross-validation\n","gs = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe_svc,\n","                  param_grid=param_grid,\n","                  scoring='accuracy',\n","                  cv=10,\n","                  refit=True,\n","                  n_jobs=-1)\n","\n","# Fit the grid search to the training data\n","gs = gs.fit(X_train, y_train)\n","\n","# Output the best score and the corresponding parameters\n","print(f'Best score: {gs.best_score_}')\n","print(f'Best parameters: {gs.best_params_}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Best score: 0.9846859903381642\n","Best parameters: {'svc__C': 100.0, 'svc__gamma': 0.001, 'svc__kernel': 'rbf'}\n"]}],"execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"cYFI2ONm0QgQ","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779120243644,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":16541,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"d3e84848-0b74-4aa3-f3dd-906a9c2b9530"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Because we set `refit=True`, scikit-learn automatically retrains the best model on the entire training dataset. We can extract this best estimator and evaluate it on the independent test dataset:"],"metadata":{"id":"w-usUDT00QgR"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Extract the best model\n","clf = gs.best_estimator_\n","\n","# Evaluate on the test dataset\n","print(f'Test accuracy: {clf.score(X_test, y_test):.3f}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Test accuracy: 0.974\n"]}],"execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"NNkDGisH0QgR","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779120354660,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":6,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"838de627-d53e-4521-87a2-9b8247795a9c"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 2. Randomized Search (`RandomizedSearchCV`)\n","\n","While grid search is powerful, it becomes computationally very expensive when dealing with large hyperparameter spaces. **Randomized search** addresses this by drawing random configurations from statistical distributions, rather than exhaustively testing every combination.\n","\n","This allows us to explore a wider range of values in a more resource-effective manner, as we can dictate exactly how many random combinations (via `n_iter`) we want to evaluate."],"metadata":{"id":"F2X_SJ7X0QgS"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["<p align=\"center\">\n","  <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rasbt/machine-learning-book/main/ch06/figures/06_11.png\" width=\"600\">\n","</p>\n"],"metadata":{"id":"1sRSn9JOhtDL"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Implementation\n","\n","We can use distributions from `scipy.stats`, such as `loguniform`, to sample continuous parameters over a specific range."],"metadata":{"id":"-K7OFO4vhzPR"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import scipy.stats\n","from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV\n","\n","# Define a log-uniform distribution for our parameters\n","param_range = scipy.stats.loguniform(0.0001, 1000.0)\n","\n","# Define the parameter distributions to sample from\n","param_distributions = [\n","    {'svc__C': param_range, 'svc__kernel': ['linear']},\n","    {'svc__C': param_range, 'svc__gamma': param_range, 'svc__kernel': ['rbf']}\n","]\n","\n","# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV (evaluating 20 random configurations)\n","rs = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=pipe_svc,\n","                        param_distributions=param_distributions,\n","                        scoring='accuracy',\n","                        refit=True,\n","                        n_iter=20,\n","                        cv=10,\n","                        random_state=1,\n","                        n_jobs=-1)\n","\n","# Fit the randomized search to the training data\n","rs = rs.fit(X_train, y_train)\n","\n","# Output the best score and parameters\n","print(f'Best score: {rs.best_score_}')\n","print(f'Best parameters: {rs.best_params_}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Best score: 0.9780676328502416\n","Best parameters: {'svc__C': np.float64(0.05971247755848463), 'svc__kernel': 'linear'}\n"]}],"execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"Ks2piT9r0QgS","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779120711826,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":3090,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"23c8cb97-6730-47b5-88e0-94243cb1ab2c"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 3. Successive Halving\n","\n","scikit-learn includes an even more efficient approach called **successive halving**. It comes in two variants: `HalvingGridSearchCV` and `HalvingRandomSearchCV`.\n","\n","### How it works:\n","\n","1. It starts by evaluating a large number of hyperparameter configurations on a small subset (sample) of the training data.\n","2. It ranks the configurations and discards the worst-performing half (or based on a defined `factor`).\n","3. In the next iteration, the remaining top configurations are evaluated again, but this time the size of the training subset is doubled.\n","4. This process of elimination and data expansion repeats until only one optimal configuration remains.\n","\n","### Implementation\n","\n","*(Note: As of the text's publication, successive halving is an experimental feature in scikit-learn and requires a special import).*"],"metadata":{"id":"UcADq4EY0QgS"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.experimental import enable_halving_search_cv\n","from sklearn.model_selection import HalvingRandomSearchCV\n","\n","# Initialize HalvingRandomSearchCV\n","hs = HalvingRandomSearchCV(\n","    estimator=pipe_svc,\n","    param_distributions=param_distributions,\n","    n_candidates='exhaust',\n","    resource='n_samples',\n","    factor=1.5,\n","    random_state=1,\n","    n_jobs=-1\n",")\n","\n","# Fit to the training data\n","hs = hs.fit(X_train, y_train)\n","\n","# Output the best score and parameters\n","print(f'Best score: {hs.best_score_}')\n","print(f'Best parameters: {hs.best_params_}')\n","\n","# Evaluate the best estimator on the test set\n","clf = hs.best_estimator_\n","print(f'Test accuracy: {hs.score(X_test, y_test):.3f}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Best score: 0.9617647058823529\n","Best parameters: {'svc__C': np.float64(4.934834261073333), 'svc__kernel': 'linear'}\n","Test accuracy: 0.982\n"]}],"execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"9vXnem3U0QgT","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779120246600,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":1321,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"92851dc7-2369-462e-8580-e215707e13d6"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 4. Algorithm Selection with Nested Cross-Validation\n","\n","Using grid search in combination with k-fold cross-validation is a highly effective way to tune the hyperparameters of a single machine learning model. However, if we want to select among *different* machine learning algorithms (e.g., deciding whether to use a Support Vector Machine or a Decision Tree), using standard k-fold cross-validation can lead to a biased estimate of the model's performance on unseen data.\n","\n","To evaluate and compare different algorithms objectively, we use **nested cross-validation**.\n","\n","### How Nested Cross-Validation Works\n","\n","Nested cross-validation separates the hyperparameter tuning step from the model evaluation step by utilizing two different cross-validation loops:\n","\n","1. **Outer Loop (Model Evaluation):** Splits the data into training and test folds.\n","2. **Inner Loop (Hyperparameter Tuning):** Takes the training fold from the outer loop and further splits it into inner training and validation folds. A grid search (or randomized search) is run on this inner loop to find the best hyperparameters.\n","\n","The best-performing model from the inner loop is then evaluated against the held-out test fold from the outer loop. A common configuration is $5 \\times 2$ cross-validation (5 outer folds, 2 inner folds), which is computationally less demanding but still reliable for estimating generalization performance.\n","\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"09uxpq4745EA"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["<p align=\"center\">\n","  <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rasbt/machine-learning-book/main/ch06/figures/06_07.png\" width=\"600\">\n","</p>\n"],"metadata":{"id":"FdUxDVekjV15"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Implementation in scikit-learn\n","\n","We can implement nested cross-validation quite easily in scikit-learn by passing our `GridSearchCV` object directly into the `cross_val_score` function.\n","\n","Here is how we can compare an SVM and a Decision Tree using nested cross-validation:"],"metadata":{"id":"9Xn4fAwFjZ3h"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["#### Evaluating the Support Vector Machine (SVM)"],"metadata":{"id":"2P3JX4ae5X1X"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV, cross_val_score\n","from sklearn.svm import SVC\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","# Define the parameter range to test\n","param_range = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0, 1000.0]\n","\n","# Define the parameter grid for the inner loop (hyperparameter tuning)\n","param_grid_svm = [\n","    {'svc__C': param_range, 'svc__kernel': ['linear']},\n","    {'svc__C': param_range, 'svc__gamma': param_range, 'svc__kernel': ['rbf']}\n","]\n","\n","# Initialize the inner loop using GridSearchCV (cv=2)\n","gs_svm = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe_svc,\n","                      param_grid=param_grid_svm,\n","                      scoring='accuracy',\n","                      cv=2)\n","\n","# Pass the GridSearchCV object to the outer loop using cross_val_score (cv=5)\n","scores_svm = cross_val_score(gs_svm, X_train, y_train,\n","                             scoring='accuracy', cv=5)\n","\n","print(f'SVM Nested CV accuracy: {np.mean(scores_svm):.3f} +/- {np.std(scores_svm):.3f}')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"zVxD25uT5L7m","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779121823920,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":4322,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"49111979-f9c5-4498-a8d4-39882c187737"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["SVM Nested CV accuracy: 0.974 +/- 0.015\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["#### Evaluating the Decision Tree"],"metadata":{"id":"H037chKG5CE_"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier\n","\n","# Define the parameter grid for the Decision Tree\n","param_grid_dt = [{'max_depth': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, None]}]\n","\n","# Initialize the inner loop (cv=2)\n","gs_dt = GridSearchCV(estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0),\n","                     param_grid=param_grid_dt,\n","                     scoring='accuracy',\n","                     cv=2)\n","\n","# Pass the GridSearchCV object to the outer loop (cv=5)\n","scores_dt = cross_val_score(gs_dt, X_train, y_train,\n","                            scoring='accuracy', cv=5)\n","\n","print(f'Decision Tree Nested CV accuracy: {np.mean(scores_dt):.3f} +/- {np.std(scores_dt):.3f}')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"a_hCIMd85H3u","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779121889471,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":399,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"e6a43a01-30f8-4c8a-e961-9cc8b5b4a1b5"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Decision Tree Nested CV accuracy: 0.934 +/- 0.016\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["By comparing the resulting mean nested CV accuracies, we can make an unbiased choice regarding which algorithm is more appropriate for our specific dataset before deploying it in the real world."],"metadata":{"id":"QvFJgLou49oo"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"hhMSOII-5HJi"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}